summary.title: Collection of Old Swedish Prose and Poetry
summary.note:
Although the binding bears the title Gamle
Svenske
Poesier (Old Swedish Poems), the manuscript contains both prose and poems, including rhymed romance, hagiographical biography, chronicle texts and legends. AM 191 fol. is probably a composite manuscript made up of various assorted manuscripts.

msItem.incipit:
I gudz namp n m och til hans loff
som ær alla tinga ophof
msItem.explicit:
ok engen for sieluwe bidher
thy gór hwar wel thet ær godh sidher
msItem.finalRubric: Et sic est finis libri skakorum
msItem.note: A rhymed paraphrase (in knittelvers) of Jacobus de Cessolis' moralising treatise on chess, Liber de ludo scaccorum(c. 1300). The treatise is an allegory that compares the feudal society with a game of chess with each pawn/chessman representing the members of society with their respective responsibilities and moral obligations.

msItem.title: King Alexander

Kung Alexander

han het anectabanus han war een
mestare j sworte konsten
msItem.explicit:
han skal vphogias j himerike
til hulka glædi læte os koma
gud fader ok son ok then hælge

msItem.title: Amicus and Amelius
De Amico et Amelio
Amicus och Amelius
msItem.rubric: De amico et amelio duobus focijs
msItem.incipit:
I them dagumen ok thima pipinus
war konunger j frankarike fod
des een pilther j bericano hans fa
dher war tyskker ok ærligen rid
dare a slæktenis wægna ok goder
oc hælager j sina lifuerne
msItem.explicit:
The wara j strid drepne for the hel
ga cristno tro skul som sagt ær j octobri manad firi dagum epter sancti
dyonisij dag radande ok styrande
medh warom herra ihesu christo som lif
wer medh fadher ok son ok then helga
anda Amen
msItem.finalRubric:
Versus Nos legimus pueros rome simul esse renatos
ffallitur ardericus nescit quia pugnat amicus
Periurusque iacet rex huic reginaque gaudet
vt lepra socium socius curaret amicum
Mactat natorum puerilia colla suorum
Tag tik hær aff lærdom ok fly falsk
het oc gom troskap oc sanning etc.
msItem.note: This romantic legend (originally from Vincentius Bellovacensis' Speculum historiale) can also be found in the collection of moralising legends Siælinna thrøst translated at the beginning of the fifteenth century at Vadstena Monastery from the Middle Low German Der selen troyst.

Snarlighan ath wettha thííad medh stak
kottom ordom huad j tæna bok ær thaa
skal man mærkia ath j tænna bok warda
rorda warastogha istorior / ssom for
dom waaro skedda
msItem.explicit:
thy som
han ser och horor saa sæger han thet
Eentidh hænde thet sik saa ath tænne

foliation.p: Foliated on top-right-hand corner. From fol. 37 to 49 there is a pagination (73-97) in pencil in the outer-top corners.

condition.p: Only the upper halves of fols 86 and 137 are extant. There is a lacuna between fols 93 and 94. The manuscript ends defectively.

layout.p: Written in long lines with 37 to 54 lines per page; rubrics and majuscules sometimes in red.

additions.p:
A note on fol. 49r reads: Anno dominj mcdxcij feria 3a infra octavas
omnium sanctorum hora decima ante
prandium Et est liber dominj johannis
gerardi cappellani monasterij
askaby Et habentur in isto libro
primo de ludo scakariorum, liber
blanzaflor De septem sapienti
bus Et de rege magne karulo.
The annalistic notes on fol. 93v, the list of things to remember on fol. 113v as well as the marian prayer on fol. 114v are also later additions.

binding.p:
Bound in a, now rather worn, binding from c. 1850; 281 114 35 . It is a half binding of marbled paper with leather back and corners. The spine bears the title Gamle
Svenske
Poesier in gold.

origin.p: The manuscript was written in the monastery of Askaby in Östergötland, Sweden at the end of the fifteenth century. The writing on fols 112v-114v, which were originally blank, was added some time in the sixteenth century.

provenance.p: In the bottom margin of fol. 115r the name EBrenner is written. The name refers to the antiquarian Elias Brenner, at whose auction Árni Magnússon probably bought the manuscript.

custEvent.p: Lent to Lund University Library ( Lunds universitets bibliotek ), Sweden, for the use of I. Björk from 1 April 1957 to 27 May 1959.
Lent to The Royal Library ( Kungliga biblioteket ), Stockholm, for the use of Helge Toldberg from 23 August to 8 September 1961.
Lent to Lund University Library ( Lunds universitets bibliotek ), Sweden, for the use of Ulf Teleman from 9 September 1962 to 28 January 1963.

Lent to Stockholm University Library ( Stockholms universitetsbibliotek ), Sweden, for the use of Patrik Åström twice: the first time from 6 March 1989 to 11 April 1990, and the second time from 29 July 1993 to 2 October 1995.
